{
  "answer": "**'The Seafarer' is included in the Falsafa corpus as Chapter 5 (\"Maey ich be me sylfum...\") of *Old English Elegies*.[^1]**\n\n**The poem does not mention worms at all—nor any connection between worms and flesh.** A full reading of the chapter confirms this.[^2]\n\nThe poem does contemplate the body's decay and transience in its homiletic second half, referring to the physical body (translated here as \"flesh-home\") as inert after death: \"Nor can his **flesh-home**, when the life has fled, / taste any sweetness or feel any sorrow, / nor stir a hand, nor think with his heart.\"[^3] This occurs amid reflections on earthly glory's decline and the need for spiritual preparation, but no worms or decomposition imagery like feasting worms appears.\n\n**Vivid descriptions of worms devouring flesh do appear in the same collection's Chapter 10 (\"Soul and Body II\"), where the soul addresses the corpse as \"food for worms\" and details \"mound-worms shall chew you,\" \"fierce worms plunder the ribs,\" etc.[^4] This may be a point of confusion, as both are Old English elegies with themes of mortality, but they are distinct works.**\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch.5, wiki card opening signature (\"the seafarer\"). [Work wiki](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/wiki/_work.card.md).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch.5 (full translation). [/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/05-maey-ich-be-me-sylfum-soth-yied-wrekan-sithas-seya/translation/].\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch.5, [p-4d6f48].\n\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, ch.10, [p-34bcc7], [p-7f7247], [p-ccab58]. [/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/].",
